e repository and confirm when done.'}, {'role': 'assistant', 'content': '[Message] from Alex(Engineer) to Mike: I have finished the task, please mark my task as finished. Outputs: Command end executed:- Implemented a Python function minPath that computes a lexicographically smallest path over a grid using a greedy neighbor selection strategy; saved it to the repository and confirmed write success. Validated behavior against provided examples.\n\nDeliverables (code paths only):\n- /Users/user1/CODE/Tester/MetaGPT/humaneval_baseline/minPath.py'}, {'role': 'user', 'content': '\n# Past Experience\n<experience>\n\n# Tool State\n\n\n# Current Plan\n[GOAL] [Message] from User to Mike: Write a Python function: \ndef minPath(grid, k):\n    """\n    Given a grid with N rows and N columns (N >= 2) and a positive integer k, \n    each cell of the grid contains a value. Every integer in the range [1, N * N]\n    inclusive appears exactly once on the cells of the grid.\n\n    You have to find the minimum path of length k in the grid. You can start\n    from any cell, and in each step you can move to any of the neighbor cells,\n    in other words, you can go to cells which share an edge with you current\n    cell.\n    Please note that a path of length k means visiting exactly k cells (not\n    necessarily distinct).\n    You CANNOT go off the grid.\n    A path A (of length k) is considered less than a path B (of length k) if\n    after making the ordered lists of the values on the cells that A and B go\n    through (let\'s call them lst_A and lst_B), lst_A is lexicographically less\n    than lst_B, in other words, there exist an integer index i (1 <= i <= k)\n    such that lst_A[i] < lst_B[i] and for any j (1 <= j < i) we have\n    lst_A[j] = lst_B[j].\n    It is guaranteed that the answer is unique.\n    Return an ordered list of the values on the cells that the minimum path go through.\n\n    Examples:\n\n        Input: grid = [ [1,2,3], [4,5,6], [7,8,9]], k = 3\n        Output: [1, 2, 1]\n\n        Input: grid = [ [5,9,3], [4,1,6], [7,8,2]], k = 1\n        Output: [1]\n    """\n \n        IMPORTANT REQUIREMENTS:  \n        1. Save the code to a file named \'minPath.py\'  \n        2. The file must be saved in the project directory: "/Users/user1/CODE/Tester/MetaGPT/humaneval_baseline"  \n        3. The file should contain ONLY the function implementation with proper imports  \n        4. Ensure the file is written to disk before completing the task  \n        \n        \n[Plan]\n[TASK_ID 1] (    )Implement in Python 3.11 the function minPath(grid: List[List[int]], k: int) -> List[int] that returns the lexicographically minimum path of length k on an N x N grid (N >= 2) where each integer 1..N*N appears exactly once. You can start from any cell and at each step move to an orthogonally adjacent neighbor; you cannot go off-grid; cells may repeat in the path. Lexicographic comparison is done on the ordered list of cell values along the path, and the answer is guaranteed unique. Implement an efficient greedy algorithm: start from the cell containing value 1 (since you can start anywhere and 1 minimizes the first element), then for each subsequent step move to the neighboring cell (up/down/left/right) with the smallest value, appending that value to the result, until length k is reached. Complexity should be O(N^2 + k). Requirements: 1) Save ONLY the function implementation (with necessary imports) to the file named minPath.py at the exact path /Users/user1/CODE/Tester/MetaGPT/humaneval_baseline/minPath.py. 2) Include only minimal proper imports (e.g., from typing import List) and no extra code (no prints, tests, or main guard). 3) Ensure the file is written to disk before reporting completion; create the directory path if it does not exist. 4) You may include the problem description as the function docstring. Use Python 3.11 standard library only. This task depends on tasks[]. [Assign to Alex]\n\n\n# Current Task\n{\'task_id\': \'1\', \'dependent_task_ids\': [], \'instruction\': \'Implement in Python 3.11 the function minPath(grid: List[List[int]], k: int) -> List[int] that returns the lexicographically minimum path of length k on an N x N grid (N >= 2) where each integer 1..N*N appears exactly once. You can start from any cell and at each step move to an orthogonally adjacent neighbor; you cannot go off-grid; cells may repeat in the path. Lexicographic comparison is done on the ordered list of cell values along the path, and the answer is guaranteed unique. Implement an efficient greedy algorithm: start from the cell containing value 1 (since you can start anywhere and 1 minimizes the first element), then for each subsequent step move to the neighboring cell (up/down/left/right) with the smallest value, appending that value to the result, until length k is reached. Complexity should be O(N^2 + k). Requirements: 1) Save ONLY the function implementation (with necessary imports) to the file named minPath.py at the exact path /Users/user1/CODE/Tester/MetaGPT/humaneval_baseline/minPath.py. 2) Include only minimal proper imports (e.g., from typing import List) and no extra code (no prints, tests, or main guard). 3) Ensure the file is written to disk before reporting completion; create the directory path if it does not exist. 4) You may include the problem description as the function docstring. Use Python 3.11 standard library only.\', \'task_type\': \'\', \'is_finished\': False, \'assignee\': \'Alex\'}\n\n# Response Language\nyou must respond in English.\n\nPay close attention to the Example provided, you can reuse the example for your current situation if it fits.\nIf you open a file, the line number is displayed at the front of each line.\nYou may use any of the available commands to create a plan or update the plan. You may output mutiple commands, they will be executed sequentially.\nIf you finish current task, you will automatically take the next task in the existing plan, use Plan.finish_current_task, 